prompt:
I'm rewriting our Connect Four move generator as a bitboard and I've been burned before by engines that "look right" — so this time verification is perft-style: walk the game tree to a fixed depth, count the nodes, compare against counts I computed independently. One wrong legal-move mask or one phantom win detection and the numbers drift; that's the whole check. No bot, no evaluation, no search heuristics — just an exact rules kernel. Files: c4.h and c4.c, C17, stdint.h only, no I/O, no heap.

    typedef struct { uint64_t red; uint64_t yel; int moves; } c4;

    void    c4_init(c4 *p);
    int     c4_drop(c4 *p, int col);
    int     c4_encode(c4 *p, const char *moves);
    int     c4_win(uint64_t bb);
    uint8_t c4_legal(const c4 *p);
    long    c4_perft(const c4 *p, int depth);

Board layout is fixed and the tests peek at raw bitboards, so follow it bit for bit: standard 7 columns x 6 rows; bit index = col*7 + row with row 0 at the BOTTOM; bit col*7 + 6 is a sentinel row that stays empty forever (that gap is what makes shift tricks safe). Red always moves first; moves counts total stones, so red is to move exactly when moves is even.

- c4_init: both boards empty, moves 0.
- c4_drop(col): the side to move drops a stone in col; it lands on the lowest empty row. Returns -1 without changing anything when col is outside 0..6, the column already holds six stones, or the game is over (either side has four in a row, or all 42 cells are filled). Returns 0 on success.
- c4_encode: reset to the empty position, then replay a NUL-terminated move string one digit per move, '0'..'6' = the column. Any bad character or illegal drop (including a move after the game ended) returns -1; a clean replay returns 0. NULL string is -1.
- c4_win(bb): 1 when bb contains four in a row in any direction. Do it with shifts, that's the point of the layout: for each direction step d in vertical 1, horizontal 7, one diagonal 6, the other 8: fold bb & (bb >> d), then check & against itself shifted by 2*d. No loops over cells.
- c4_legal: a byte whose bit c is set when column c can take a stone — and 0 whenever the game is over. Movegen returning empty at terminal positions is what makes perft prune correctly.
- c4_perft(p, depth): number of game-tree nodes at exactly that depth below p, counting move sequences (transpositions counted every time — this is a tree walk, no dedup, no memo). depth 0 is 1 by definition, negative depth is 0. A finished game has no children.

The suite pins node counts at every depth 1 through 6 from the start position and from three replayed fixtures (a full-column position, a double-threat tactical position, and a jumbled midgame), plus raw bitboard values after encoding and the shift-detector on hand-built masks. If your counts differ from mine at any depth, something in drop/legal/win is wrong — the counts are not up for negotiation.

make test is the gate. Makefile, mintest.h and test_c4.c are fixed.
